senses.definition: Move to a better position; advance to a higher level/rank
examples: She moved up from secretary to senior manager in just a few years.

senses.definition: Move upward, from a lower spatial location to a higher one
examples: She put her hand on his shoulder and moved it up along the back of his neck.

senses.definition: Choose SB/STH among a number of alternatives
examples: She picked out the best-looking dress she could find.

senses.definition: Detect/be noticed among a group of things or people
examples: My mum could easily be picked out in the picture.

senses.definition: Remove STH that was previously put up or put in place
examples: After the exhibition, they took the paintings down.

senses.definition: Destroy, kill, or disable
examples: The terrorists tried to take down the President's plane.

senses.definition: Take SB to a place, esp. further south or at a lower level
examples: My dad decided to take us down to Florida.

senses.definition: (+ with) Continue doing STH after stopping
examples: We might as well get on with it if we want to finish on time.

senses.definition: Get on board some form of public transportation (train, bus, plane, elevator)
examples: He got on the bus to go to school.

senses.definition: Return STH to its original owner/provider
examples: It’s nice to be able to give back to the community.

senses.definition: Give STH to SB by holding it in one’s hand and offering it to them
examples: She turned around to hand over her keys to her husband.

senses.definition: Surrender control or responsibility for STH/SB to SB else, esp. officially
examples: The government isn’t willing to hand over power to local authorities.

senses.definition: Express or represent the most important/representative facts, ideas, or characteristics of SB/STH, especially in a brief manner
examples: He summed up the whole discussion in just a few minutes.

senses.definition: Leave one’s place of residence permanently
examples: Our neighbour is going to move out next month.

senses.definition: Become detached or removed from a larger whole
examples: The button is coming off my shirt.

senses.definition: Appear or seem to be a particular way
examples: He was tired and not prepared, and so came off poorly in the interview.

senses.definition: Be finished with STH; have completed STH
examples: The team just came off an incredibly successful season.

senses.definition: Circulate or communicate; give STH to SB after receiving it from SB else (information, ideas, object)
examples: I got this message this morning and was asked to pass it on to you.

senses.definition: Transmit from one generation to the next (traditions, beliefs, skills, possessions)
examples: These ancient traditions have been passed on from generation to generation.

senses.definition: Die (euphemism)
examples: She has been very depressed since her mother passed on.

senses.definition: Provide a place for SB to live or stay
examples: The family took her in when she was abandoned by her parents.

senses.definition: Fully understand or grasp the meaning of STH
examples: You have to explain more thoroughly; it’s too difficult to take in.

senses.definition: Deceive by behaving in a dishonest way
examples: He was very convincing, so I was easily taken in.

senses.definition: Put something on a surface or on the ground
examples: He carried the bags to his room and set them down.

senses.definition: Do what is needed to solve a problem, conflict or difficult situation
examples: A few ideas were raised to sort out the company’s financial issues.

senses.definition: Find out information so as to understand STH
examples: He will need some time to sort out the reasons for his failure.

senses.definition: Take action about STH after a previous action or thing, esp. so as to reinforce its effect
examples: You won’t be cured immediately after the operation; you will have to follow up with therapy.

senses.definition: Try to find more information about STH
examples: Detectives are following up on a few promising leads.

senses.definition: Be clearly perceived, noticed or seen (feeling, emotion, quality)
examples: Her disappointment came through by the tone of her voice.

senses.definition: Reach success or a desired goal despite difficulty
examples: He worked really hard, and despite some difficulties, he came through in the end.

senses.definition: Arrive at a destination; come into view (train, ship)
examples: We had to wait for a ship to come through and rescue us.

senses.definition: Adopt a quieter and steadier lifestyle
examples: I just want to fall in love with the right guy and settle down.

senses.definition: Become calmer, quieter, more orderly
examples: We need things to settle down before we can make a serious decision.

senses.definition: Get into a comfortable position, either sitting or lying
examples: When he reached the top of the hill, he settled down in the grass to have a rest.

senses.definition: Come in the area near STH/SB
examples: He came around to my room and kissed me goodnight.

senses.definition: (+ to) Convert to an opinion or decision
examples: I believe she will come around to our way of thinking eventually.

senses.definition: Happen again as a regular event, at its usual time
examples: You’ll have to wait until summer comes around.

senses.definition: (+ for) Do SB’s work temporarily because they cannot or will not do it themselves
examples: I had to fill in for her yesterday because she was ill.

senses.definition: (+ on) Give SB extra or missing information they want or need
examples: She filled Carol in on the plan.

senses.definition: Put material or substance into STH in order to make it full or complete
examples: All the remaining holes had to be filled in with concrete.

senses.definition: Give to each of a large number of people
examples: The committee gave out more than 100 copies in the last meeting.

senses.definition: Make known openly or publicly
examples: You should be more careful and not give out your phone number so easily.

senses.definition: Collapse/fail; stop functioning properly (heart, knees)
examples: At 95 years of age, her heart finally gave out.

senses.definition: Cease resistance to (liking/temptation/habit, or to SB’s demands/control)
examples: She shouldn’t give in to her children’s demands.

senses.definition: Progress or proceed with an activity
examples: You will learn as you go along.

senses.definition: Act in cooperation or express agreement
examples: The Democrats are not likely to go along with the plan.

senses.definition: Go to a place or event, esp. without much planning
examples: Would you like to go along with us to the party?

senses.definition: Separate a part (or become separate) from a larger piece
examples: He accidentally broke off a piece of wood from the fence.

senses.definition: Stop speaking, especially suddenly
examples: “There is something that…” He broke off abruptly.

senses.definition: Put an end to STH (relationship, discussion, talks, negotiations)
examples: They broke off diplomatic relations in 1986.

senses.definition: Delay until a later time or date
examples: Now that I had more free time, there was no excuse to put off exercising any longer.

senses.definition: Cause to feel intense dislike
examples: The bad smell put everyone off.

senses.definition: Take place or happen/occur, esp. unexpectedly
examples: I did not expect this to come about.

senses.definition: Stop operating or functioning
examples: Non-profitable companies were closed down.

senses.definition: Put one thing inside another; include or insert
examples: You need to put in your contact details in case there is a problem.

senses.definition: Invest or devote so as to achieve STH (time, effort, work)
examples: I put in ten hours a day at the office.

senses.definition: Begin a course of action, usually with a specific purpose/objective in mind
examples: We set about laying the table before our guests arrived.
